answer: The kitchen; room where food is prepared and cooked.
The refrigerator; appliance for keeping food cold and fresh.
The living room; main room for relaxing and entertaining guests.
The bedroom; room for sleeping and resting.
The bathroom; room with toilet, sink, and usually shower or bathtub.
The hallway or corridor; passage connecting rooms in a home.
The basement or cellar; underground storage area of a building.
The attic; space directly under the roof, often used for storage.
The balcony; outdoor platform attached to an upper floor.
The terrace or patio; outdoor area for sitting, usually at ground level.
The stove or cooker; appliance for cooking with heat.
The oven; enclosed compartment for baking and roasting food.
The dishwasher; machine that automatically washes dishes.
The washing machine; appliance for cleaning clothes automatically.
The dryer; machine that dries wet laundry using heat.
The sofa or couch; upholstered seating furniture for multiple people.
The armchair; comfortable chair with armrests for one person.
The cupboard or wardrobe; tall storage furniture with doors.
The chest of drawers; furniture with drawers for storing clothes.
The shelf or bookcase; furniture with horizontal surfaces for storage.
The carpet or rug; fabric floor covering for warmth and decoration.
The curtain; fabric hanging at windows for privacy and decoration.
The lamp; device that produces artificial light.
The mirror; reflective glass surface for viewing one's appearance.
The pillow or cushion; soft support for the head or body.
The blanket; warm covering used on beds for sleeping.
The alarm clock; device that rings at a set time to wake someone.
The vacuum cleaner; electric device that sucks up dirt from floors.
The broom; cleaning tool with bristles for sweeping floors.
The bucket or pail; container with handle for carrying liquids.
The cloth or rag; piece of fabric for cleaning surfaces.
The towel; absorbent fabric for drying hands or body.
The trash can or rubbish bin; container for disposing waste.
The garbage or rubbish; waste materials to be thrown away.
The key; metal device for opening locks on doors.
The door; movable barrier for entering or exiting a room.
The window; glass opening in a wall for light and air.
The heating system; equipment that warms a building or room.
The electrical outlet or socket; point where devices connect to electricity.
The faucet or tap; device controlling water flow from pipes.
To clean; to remove dirt and make something tidy and hygienic.
To tidy up; to organize and put things back in their place.
To wash the dishes; to clean plates, cups, and utensils after eating.
To rinse or wash; to clean dishes or surfaces with water.
To wipe or mop; to clean surfaces by rubbing with cloth.
To vacuum; to clean floors or carpets using a vacuum cleaner.
To sweep; to clean floors by pushing dirt with a broom.
To iron; to press clothes with a heated device to remove wrinkles.
To wash; to clean something using water and usually soap.
To dry; to remove moisture from something using heat or air.
To hang up; to suspend clothing or items on hooks or lines.
The laundry; clothes and linens that need washing or are being washed.
The waste or trash; discarded materials no longer needed.
To dispose of; to get rid of waste in proper manner.
To recycle; to process waste materials for reuse instead of disposal.
The rent; regular payment for using a property or apartment.
The tenant; person who rents and lives in someone else's property.
The landlord; person who owns property and rents it to others.
The additional costs; utility and maintenance expenses beyond rent.
The security deposit; money paid upfront to protect against property damage.
The electricity; electrical power used for lighting and appliances.
The gas; fuel used for heating, cooking, and hot water.
The water; liquid supplied to homes for drinking, washing, and cooking.
The bill or invoice; document showing amount owed for services.
To get up; to rise from bed or a seated position.
To get dressed; to put on clothing.
To shower; to wash one's body under running water.
To shave; to remove hair from face or body.
To have breakfast; to eat the first meal of the day.
To have lunch; to eat the midday meal.
To have dinner; to eat the evening meal.
To go shopping; to buy groceries or other items from stores.
To cook; to prepare food by heating and combining ingredients.
To bake; to cook food in an oven, especially bread or cakes.
Varied or diverse; having variety and not monotonous or repetitive.
Cozy or comfortable; creating a pleasant, relaxed atmosphere.
Tidy or neat; well-organized and properly arranged.
Messy or untidy; disorganized and not properly arranged.
Clean; free from dirt, stains, or impurities.
Dirty; covered with or containing dirt or stains.
The household; home and family living together, including domestic tasks.
The housework; tasks necessary for maintaining a clean, functioning home.
The daily life; everyday routine activities and regular occurrences.
The routine; regular sequence of actions performed daily or regularly.
To move house; to relocate to a different residence or apartment.
To move in; to begin living in a new home or apartment.
To move out; to leave one's residence permanently.
To renovate; to repair and improve a building or room.
To furnish; to equip a room with furniture and decorations.
To decorate; to add ornamental items to make something attractive.
To repair or fix; to restore something broken to working condition.
Broken; not functioning properly or damaged beyond immediate use.
To function or work; to operate correctly and as intended.
The craftsman or tradesperson; skilled worker who does manual repairs.
The neighbor; person living in an adjacent house or apartment.
The neighborhood; surrounding area where one lives and nearby residents.
To air out or ventilate; to open windows for fresh air circulation.
To lock; to secure a door or window with a key.
To unlock; to open a lock with a key.
The viewing or inspection; visit to look at property before renting.
A contract or agreement, especially an employment contract.
To apply for a job or position.
A job application or application documents.
An employer or company that hires workers.
Overtime hours worked beyond regular schedule.
End of workday or leisure time.
To fire or dismiss an employee.
To employ or give someone a job.
To sign a document or contract.
To lead or manage a team.
To complete or finish a task.
A requirement or demand for a job.
A cover letter for job applications.
A reference letter or work certificate.
Knowledge or skills in an area.
Able to work well in teams.
Communicative or good at expressing ideas.
Notice period before leaving a job.
Working from home or remote work.
A business trip or work travel.
An order or assignment from clients.
A sick day or absence from work.
A school report card or certificate.
A term paper or essay assignment.
To review or follow up on material.
A grade or mark on work.
To pass an exam or test.
A university seminar or discussion class.
To memorize or learn by heart.
Skills or knowledge in an area.
To comprehend or grasp an idea.
Adult education center or community college.
Timetable or schedule showing departure and arrival times for public transport.
To change trains, buses, or other transport; to transfer.
Platform or track at a train station.
To validate or stamp a ticket.
Parking garage or multi-story car park.
To refuel or fill up with gas.
To check out of a hotel.
To visit or view a sight.
To be delayed or running late.
To cancel a booking or reservation.
To book or make a reservation.
To miss a train, bus, or deadline.
To try, taste, or sample something.
To exchange or return an item.
Department or section in a store.
To reserve or book a table.
Daily special or dish of the day.
To taste good; to like the taste.
Bill or check at a restaurant.
To pay separately or split the bill.
